item.title: Cyprus Plan Falls Short of Bailout Goal
item.description: Cyprus went on a collision course with the euro zone by sending a draft bill to Parliament that would raise less revenue from a controversial deposit tax than required for an international bailout.

item.title: Syria Accuses Rebels of Firing Chemical Weapon
item.description: Syria's government accused rebels of firing a chemical weapon, the first such allegation against the rebel insurgency in two years of fighting, which the rebels denied and blamed on the government.

item.title: Wave of Deadly Attacks Hits Baghdad
item.description: Dozens of Iraqis were killed or wounded in a barrage of car bombs on the eve of the 10th anniversary of the start of the U.S.-led invasion.

item.title: Militant Linked to Pearl's Death Arrested
item.description: Pakistani authorities arrested a militant who they say was connected with the murder of Wall Street Journal reporter Daniel Pearl in 2002.

item.title: Zimbabwe Passes New Constitution
item.description: Zimbabwe election commission said the public had approved a new constitution, a victory shared by bitter political rivals that now paves the way for national elections later this year.

item.title: Lew Meets China's Power Elites
item.description: China President Xi Jinping and U.S. Treasury Secretary Jacob Lew acknowledged their diplomatic differences but said cooperation could bring mutual benefits during their first meeting in Beijing.

item.title: India Party Pulls Government Support
item.description: The Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam party, a key ally of the ruling Congress-led United Progressive Alliance, withdrew its support from the federal government.

item.title: Chinese Investors Get Picky Over Visa Program
item.description: Johannes von Trapp, a scion of the family depicted in "The Sound of Music," is trying to lure foreigners to invest in his New England lodge, dangling U.S. visas as part of the deal. But would-be investors are getting pickier.

item.title: U.K. Leadership Has Faith in Austerity
item.description: When U.K. Treasury chief George Osborne announces his budget Wednesday, he is expected to stick with his austerity message.

item.title: India Extends Ban on Italian Envoy
item.description: India's Supreme Court extended a travel ban on the Italian ambassador until further notice, sparking a debate on diplomatic immunity and deepening tensions over a year-long international row between India and Italy.

item.title: Syrians Find No Refuge in Greece
item.description: On the shores of Lesvos, Syria's refugee crisis is crashing up against Greece's migrant-policy mess. Many Syrian refugees who have tried to enter Europe through Greece, hoping to seek haven in northern countries, have instead found a harsh welcome.

item.title: Philippines Reproductive Health Law on Hold
item.description: The Philippine Supreme Court ordered the government to suspend the implementation of a recently passed reproductive health law aimed at slowing the Southeast Asian nation's population growth.

item.title: Italy, India Escalate War of Words
item.description: Italy and India escalated their war of words, damping hopes for a solution to a diplomatic row sparked by Rome's refusal to send two marines back to India to stand trial on murder charges.

item.title: India Bus Crash Kills Dozens
item.description: A bus packed with passengers crashed through a guard rail and fell off a bridge in western India early Tuesday, killing at least 37 people.

item.title: Palestinians Await More Aid
item.description: Western backers of the Palestinian Authority are grappling with how to bring financial stability to a government crippled by international aid shortfalls and Israeli sanctions.

item.title: BOJ Official Makes Rare Return
item.description: In a rare move, a senior Bank of Japan official credited with coming up with unconventional deflation-fighting measures will be reappointed.

item.title: Australia Leader Under Voter Pressure
item.description: Twice as many of Australia's voters prefer former leader Kevin Rudd over embattled Prime Minister Julia Gillard, an opinion poll showed Monday.

item.title: Nations Need $1.6 Billion for TB Fight, Authorities Say
item.description: The World Health Organization and the Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis and Malaria said they need an extra $1.6 billion a year at minimum to fight tuberculosis in poor countries—a large chunk of it to prevent and treat drug-resistant strains of the ancient airborne disease.

item.title: Painting Identified as Rembrandt Self-Portrait
item.description: A painting donated to Britain's National Trust by the estate of a wealthy supporter has been identified as a Rembrandt self-portrait worth £20 million ($30.2 million), the heritage body said.

item.title: Pope Begins Ministry With Call to Aid Poor
item.description: The Catholic Church's first New World pontiff formally began his ministry with a call for politicians, priests and others in positions of power to protect society's poorest members.

item.title: Congolese Warlord Turns Himself In
item.description: A Congolese warlord who has come to symbolize that country's intractable conflict surrendered to the U.S. embassy in Rwanda.

item.title: ANC Fires Youth League Leaders
item.description: South Africa's ruling African National Congress disbanded the leadership of its youth league, a once-potent voice in national politics whose influence has waned after the expulsion of its rabble-rousing leader.

item.title: Focus on Survival in Syrian Capital
item.description: For most residents in the Syrian capital, war governs every detail of life. Damascus residents, whether they are opponents and supporters of the regime, have honed their survival skills.

item.title: Questions on Cuban Snails? Take a Peek in Mr. Cueto's Hall
item.description: The Havana émigré has built a one-man Smithsonian to his homeland in a Washington apartment.

item.title: A Trumpet in the Wild
item.description: Learning about life and loss while caring for orphaned elephants in Zambia's Kafue National Park.

item.title: Belgian Train Museum Had a Hard Time Getting on Track
item.description: The latest problem for this train-mad country: too many historic steam engines.

item.title: Afghan Church Endures
item.description: Inside Italy's embassy, a Catholic priest operates Afghanistan's only church.

item.title: Photos of the Day: March 18
item.description: In today's pictures, eggs are dyed for Easter in Germany, police clash with protesters in Paris, a private plane crashes in Indiana, and more.
